🏔️ Project Vertex: Spatial Versioning Protocol for 3D Environments

Project Vertex is a Git-integrated middleware designed to bridge the gap between destructive 3D asset management and modern, non-linear version control systems (VCS). By deconstructing monolithic .blend files into versionable text-based metadata, Vertex brings the power of CI/CD to 3D production pipelines.

🔴 The Problem: The "Binary Blob" Constraint

In modern 3D production, software like Blender saves project data in monolithic Binary Large Objects (BLOBs). While efficient for local storage, these files are "black boxes" to standard development tools.

Indecipherable Diffs: Standard VCS (like Git) treats any change—even moving a single vertex—as a complete rewrite of the binary file.

Workflow Chaos: Two artists cannot work on the same scene simultaneously without risk of overwriting data.

Version Inflation: Teams rely on "Save As" redundancy (e.g., Scene_v01.blend, Scene_v02.blend), leading to massive storage waste.

🟢 The Solution: Atomic Serialization & Middleware

Vertex is a protocol that deconstructs a 3D scene into Atomic Metadata Fragments.

Core Architecture

Instead of versioning the .blend file, Vertex serializes the scene into a Domain-Specific Schema (DSS):

Domain Segment

Data Captured (via Blender bpy API)

spatial.json

Hierarchical transforms (LOC/ROT/SCALE) and parent-child relationships.

shaders.json

Node graph structures, material properties, and texture URIs.

lighting.json

Photometric data, energy levels, and HDRI configurations.

logic.json

Modifier stacks (Subdivision, Boolean, Array) and parameters.

✨ Key Features

👻 Visual Delta-Tracking ("Ghosts")

A Developer reads code diffs; a 3D Artist needs Visual Diffs. Vertex compares the current state vs. a previous commit and projects transparent wireframe "ghosts" directly into the 3D viewport.

Green Overlays: Modified/Moved objects.

Red Overlays: Deleted objects.

🤖 AI-Assisted Semantic Merging

When two branches modify the same object, traditional Git fails. Vertex uses Gemini 2.5 Flash to analyze spatial relationships and artistic intent to resolve conflicts (e.g., merging a lighting change from Branch A with a geometry change from Branch B).

⏳ The Spatial Time Machine

Using a "Time-Travel Slider" in the Blender UI, users can scrub through the Git history of a 3D world in real-time, watching the environment evolve without opening separate files.

🛠️ Technical Workflow (MVP)

Extraction Layer: A Python-based "Watcher" inside Blender monitors bpy.data.

Versioning Layer: A hidden .vertex directory managed by a background Git process.

Conflict Layer: A semantic logic gate (Gemini API) to resolve overlapping 3D changes.

Reconstruction Layer: A script that "re-materializes" the scene from JSON metadata upon branch checkout.

🏆 Hackathon Rubric Alignment

Track 2 (Web Systems & Interaction): We transform the Blender Viewport into a Reality-Blending Interface, where technical Git commands translate into physical changes in a 3D simulation.

Track 5 (Open Innovation): We are building the "impossible"—a Git-native 3D engine that handles non-linear creative evolution with 95% less storage overhead than standard methods.

